Find all real numbers $x$ satisfying \[\frac{2x-5}{x+3} \ge 2.\](Give your answer in interval notation.)
inference: We begin by subtracting 2 from both sides of the inequality to get \[\frac{2x-5}{x+3} - 2 \ge 0.\]Combining the terms on the left-hand side, we get \[\frac{2x-5-2(x+3)}{x+3} \ge 0,\]which simplifies to \[\frac{-11}{x+3} \ge 0.\]Since $-11$ is negative, the left-hand side is nonnegative when $x+3$ is negative.  Therefore, the solution to the inequality is $x+3<0$, or $x<-3$.  In interval notation, this is $\boxed{(-\infty,-3)}$. Final Answer: $\boxed{(-\infty,-3)}$. I hope it is correct.
ground_truth:
Subtracting $2$ from both sides, we get
\begin{align*}
 \frac{2x-5}{x+3} - 2 &\ge 0 \\
 \frac{2x-5 - 2(x+3)}{x+3} &\geq 0 \\
 \frac{-11}{x+3} &\ge 0.
\end{align*}Therefore, we must have $x+3 < 0,$ so $x < -3.$ Therefore, the solution set is $\boxed{ (-\infty, -3) }.$
